1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:08,691
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassa

2
00:00:09,041 --> 00:00:35,843
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed, Noble and Fully Self-Enlightened One Many thanks for your questions

3
00:00:38,253 --> 00:00:43,762
There are only so many topics that you can talk about, probably a dozen or more.

4
00:00:45,124 --> 00:00:52,475
And what a question does is it sort of makes you look at a particular topic from a slightly different angle.

5
00:00:53,197 --> 00:00:56,442
So it allows a bit of creativity rather than coming out of my usual.

6
00:00:59,167 --> 00:00:59,628
Yes.

7
00:01:01,049 --> 00:01:05,356
I'm not going to answer these in order because they work better if I jumble them around a bit.

8
00:01:06,772 --> 00:01:14,063
Just the first one is concerning the experience that we have during the day.

9
00:01:15,165 --> 00:01:21,635
So the question is I've noticed over the past three or four days that the same sits each day have the same quality of energy.

10
00:01:22,355 --> 00:01:27,143
So first thing in the morning is good and late afternoon, early afternoon the energy is low.

11
00:01:27,662 --> 00:01:29,626
And late after an evening, it's good again.

12
00:01:30,025 --> 00:01:35,753
Is it possible that we have a distinct rhythm of energy like a daily pattern?

13
00:01:35,772 --> 00:01:38,075
Yeah, I think most people experience that.

14
00:01:38,096 --> 00:01:46,527
Most people have a... And I mean midday is a classic time when you do, when the body energy does go down.

15
00:01:46,546 --> 00:01:48,108
You're supposed to have a rest after lunch.

16
00:01:48,129 --> 00:01:53,415
As you know, I'm an aficionado of the siesta.

17
00:01:54,016 --> 00:01:56,319
I've no model problems with that.

18
00:01:56,941 --> 00:01:59,243
So people are different.

19
00:01:59,263 --> 00:02:00,766
They have different metabolisms, don't they?

20
00:02:00,805 --> 00:02:03,409
People are good risers and some people are poor risers.

21
00:02:03,469 --> 00:02:05,132
People like to stay awake at night.

22
00:02:05,212 --> 00:02:16,467
I mean, I know one person, his rhythm is, he works till one o'clock in the morning.

23
00:02:16,486 --> 00:02:18,729
So when he comes here, it's a hell realm.

24
00:02:19,991 --> 00:02:27,461
So I have to adjust things for him because it's silly really because he spends most of his time falling asleep.

25
00:02:28,342 --> 00:02:30,506
Because that's when he's awake.

26
00:02:30,947 --> 00:02:33,469
He's awake when we're asleep and asleep when we're awake.

27
00:02:34,872 --> 00:02:37,977
So everybody has these different rhythms.

28
00:02:39,838 --> 00:02:44,885
But the important thing is to know the difference between

29
00:02:45,557 --> 00:02:50,022
that which is natural to us and that which we're laying on top through bad habit.

30
00:02:50,864 --> 00:02:54,027
So the bad habit would be that when we feel tired we simply go to sleep.

31
00:02:54,908 --> 00:02:57,010
We don't question it, that's all.

32
00:02:58,072 --> 00:03:11,668
And as you know, we often go to sleep or get dozy often when we're fed up with things or a bit depressed or we just, I'll have a sleep now.

33
00:03:12,489 --> 00:03:15,092
And it's a lovely form of self-annihilation.

34
00:03:15,932 --> 00:03:18,497
And as you know, there's no suffering in oblivion.

35
00:03:19,298 --> 00:03:23,384
I mean, that's the lovely thing about oblivion.

36
00:03:25,007 --> 00:03:26,770
It's like there's nothing there.

37
00:03:27,031 --> 00:03:27,831
There's nobody there.

38
00:03:27,872 --> 00:03:28,854
There's no suffering or anything.

39
00:03:29,794 --> 00:03:34,342
It's just that we insist on waking up.

40
00:03:34,361 --> 00:03:36,125
So then, you see, there's this habit.

41
00:03:36,626 --> 00:03:38,990
Now remember, these habits are dispositions.

42
00:03:39,050 --> 00:03:39,830
They are...

43
00:03:40,604 --> 00:04:06,865
wells of potential energy so we don't tend to think of dullness and lethargy as energy we tend to think of them as a sort of a negative thing a loss of energy but it's not if you look at them closely they're dragging you down into a black hole which is not the same as tiredness tiredness is a clean energy and when you wake up from it you do feel refreshed

44
00:04:07,115 --> 00:04:16,156
But it's often the case that when you oversleep or when you're sleeping to escape something, sometimes they get worse than when you first went into sleep.

45
00:04:17,658 --> 00:04:21,107
So it's really distinguishing those two on a retreat.

46
00:04:21,982 --> 00:04:22,884
Knowing the distinction.

47
00:04:22,983 --> 00:04:23,906
It's not always easy.

48
00:04:24,326 --> 00:04:36,011
I mean, as you know, the usual thing I say is the first three days, there's a sort of natural tiredness comes because of the imbalance in most people's sleep.

49
00:04:36,733 --> 00:04:41,543
They're either oversleeping like that or they're undersleeping or they're not sleeping well or something, you know.

50
00:04:42,485 --> 00:04:43,485
That's normally ironed out.

51
00:04:43,586 --> 00:04:45,648
And I do see it on people's faces.

52
00:04:45,728 --> 00:04:48,911
That's one of the things that you see after three days.

53
00:04:48,971 --> 00:04:51,454
The face changes dramatically.

54
00:04:52,295 --> 00:04:58,781
Partly because, I think, of the sleep business, but also because just for a moment they've dropped the cares and woes of life.

55
00:05:00,083 --> 00:05:04,088
Forget about it finally, just for a day.

56
00:05:05,990 --> 00:05:06,730
It is remarkable.

57
00:05:06,790 --> 00:05:12,036
And what you see is the modern stress, you see,

58
00:05:13,298 --> 00:05:21,144
I remember when I used to go and visit up to the uplands of Sri Lanka where they were living really the old agricultural life.

59
00:05:21,204 --> 00:05:22,365
They lived with the seasons.

60
00:05:24,028 --> 00:05:26,089
They lived very, very close to the earth.

61
00:05:26,670 --> 00:05:27,531
It was just a hut.

62
00:05:27,670 --> 00:05:33,396
They had a bit of, they had maybe a small bit of furniture they'd bashed up together.

63
00:05:34,156 --> 00:05:37,120
And the land up there is plentiful.

64
00:05:37,379 --> 00:05:40,403
Up on the highlands, I mean, it's just so lush.

65
00:05:40,382 --> 00:05:42,505
And the rainfall is twice a year.

66
00:05:42,547 --> 00:05:43,908
The monsoon comes twice.

67
00:05:45,050 --> 00:05:51,802
And there isn't that existential fear, you know, like you get when there's an economic crisis.

68
00:05:51,862 --> 00:05:54,966
As far as they're concerned, they're still going to get curry.

69
00:05:54,987 --> 00:05:55,728
It's not a problem.

70
00:05:55,747 --> 00:05:56,889
It's just there.

71
00:05:57,545 --> 00:06:03,014
And you see, you see a very different sort of atmosphere about them.

72
00:06:03,033 --> 00:06:09,163
Obviously much more relaxed, much more at peace, much more at ease, you see.

73
00:06:09,244 --> 00:06:13,170
Now, that's one of the blessings, isn't it, that we give with Metta.

74
00:06:14,050 --> 00:06:23,906
It's to live in ease, you see, not to have this constant worry and stuff that the modern society really pushes on top of us.

75
00:06:26,975 --> 00:06:30,858
As a monk I, when going out to the Easter course, I escaped all this.

76
00:06:30,879 --> 00:06:39,908
I know what it's like when you know you're going to get lunch and you have only a few clothes and you know that's enough and they'll last for years.

77
00:06:40,850 --> 00:06:43,153
And you have a roof over your head and it's always warm.

78
00:06:43,572 --> 00:06:47,317
You never get that cold that you can't put a jumper on and feel warm.

79
00:06:48,959 --> 00:06:51,901
So this little escapade here, Satipan, has been a bit of an awakening.

80
00:06:53,451 --> 00:07:02,269
Because here all I've been assailed with constant worries and it's wonderful, the real awakening.

81
00:07:02,290 --> 00:07:05,196
I was living in a false Nirvana, that's what it was.

82
00:07:05,216 --> 00:07:15,156
And I must say this, the laying of this car park and the placing of that statue, that's it.

83
00:07:15,507 --> 00:07:19,851
It's taken two years to get to a point where there is really nothing more to be done.

84
00:07:20,052 --> 00:07:25,199
I mean, there are always one or two things, but all the big stuff's gone, and that's it, really.

85
00:07:25,939 --> 00:07:40,336
The only thing is hopefully in time we can place some small buildings or something for people in wheelchairs, wheelchair access, which we haven't got.

86
00:07:40,377 --> 00:07:44,923
You know, and a proper toilet pan for disabled people.

87
00:07:46,911 --> 00:07:48,334
So yes, that's that then.

88
00:07:48,954 --> 00:07:52,660
So that's the only thing with your rhythm.

89
00:07:52,680 --> 00:08:01,432
So it's natural to feel tired at certain times of the day and just to know that that's physical and not an unwholesome mental disposition or so.

90
00:08:04,517 --> 00:08:06,860
And finally, of course, you've got to take that into daily life.

91
00:08:08,182 --> 00:08:12,709
You can't make the effort here and then in daily life you just go berserk and sleep all the time.

92
00:08:12,730 --> 00:08:16,394
It's just like the practice has to go into your daily life.

93
00:08:17,471 --> 00:08:24,461
So that you're always gently lifting your energy.

94
00:08:25,423 --> 00:08:27,185
And energy is just like anything else.

95
00:08:27,225 --> 00:08:29,067
The more you exercise it, the more you have of it.

96
00:08:30,970 --> 00:08:33,975
It's not as though you've only got so much energy and that's the end of it.

97
00:08:34,394 --> 00:08:38,421
I'm sure there's a limit, physically anyway.

98
00:08:38,441 --> 00:08:40,003
You can't be running up Everest.

99
00:08:41,024 --> 00:08:46,010
But I think we've got much more energy than we think we have.

100
00:08:47,341 --> 00:08:54,948
or potential for more energy than we think we have.

101
00:08:54,969 --> 00:08:56,554
Does any questions arise from that?

102
00:08:56,654 --> 00:08:58,140
Any clarifications?

103
00:08:58,160 --> 00:08:58,481
Yeah.

104
00:08:59,288 --> 00:09:05,697
You describe sloth and torpor as an energy that you look at and investigate.

105
00:09:05,716 --> 00:09:11,205
But I find that if I try and be wrapped, I get wrapped up in it and... Fall asleep.

106
00:09:11,245 --> 00:09:11,946
Yeah.

107
00:09:12,547 --> 00:09:12,826
So, yeah.

108
00:09:13,989 --> 00:09:19,576
Well, when... Sloth and torpor... Sloth and torpor.

109
00:09:22,259 --> 00:09:24,283
They're a sort of early translation.

110
00:09:25,063 --> 00:09:25,784
And...

111
00:09:27,115 --> 00:09:29,558
It tends to put a sort of moral no-no on it.

112
00:09:30,639 --> 00:09:31,802
It's sort of a moral, you know.

113
00:09:32,322 --> 00:09:36,489
So the, I tend to prefer dullness and lethargy and let people off a bit.

114
00:09:38,010 --> 00:09:42,317
I more feel guilty and shameful, which you ought to, of course.

115
00:09:42,336 --> 00:09:43,719
I mean, that's the truth of it.

116
00:09:44,120 --> 00:09:46,423
But the modern person doesn't like that.

117
00:09:47,753 --> 00:09:57,744
Yes, there are various things you can do, of course, which is to put yourself in a position where it's difficult to fall asleep.

118
00:09:58,625 --> 00:10:03,669
And it depends on the strength of the dullness and lethargy.

119
00:10:03,990 --> 00:10:07,434
So, one can open one's eyes and still feel it.

120
00:10:08,075 --> 00:10:10,538
You see, you're feeling the sensations.

121
00:10:11,378 --> 00:10:30,619
that's what you're doing so if it's a dullness in the mind your attention is in this area you see just feeling the dullness and you can stand up and you can walk and you'd be surprised when you keep making that effort to be aware of these feelings

122
00:10:31,493 --> 00:10:36,721
which are neutral feelings, they're not painful, they're quite restful actually.

123
00:10:39,524 --> 00:10:47,655
It's like the energy draws back into the watching, into the knowing, and you become bright, absolutely bright.

124
00:10:47,716 --> 00:10:49,097
It's like walking into a cloud.

125
00:10:50,500 --> 00:10:55,206
It's like that, it's like being in a fog.

126
00:10:56,469 --> 00:10:59,072
You're awake, you see, but you're there with these feelings.

127
00:10:59,813 --> 00:11:01,416
And remember, you're not trying to get rid of them,

128
00:11:02,527 --> 00:11:05,894
You're not trying to do anything to them.

129
00:11:05,914 --> 00:11:09,724
Just like all these forms of energy, you're just allowing it to dissipate.

130
00:11:11,027 --> 00:11:21,530
And as it dissipates, you're losing a bit of the energy from that disposition, sankhāra, from that particular habit.

131
00:11:21,831 --> 00:11:28,462
So that's why you've got to take it to daily life, because if you don't, you go back, you reinforce the old habit.

132
00:11:29,083 --> 00:11:32,568
So every time you come to meditation retreat, you keep having to suffer the same things.

133
00:11:36,014 --> 00:11:36,696
There's a lot of it.

134
00:11:40,702 --> 00:11:43,527
We're not going to run out of it.

135
00:11:43,547 --> 00:11:45,190
Well, not for a while.

136
00:11:50,570 --> 00:11:52,373
I think it is actually.

137
00:11:52,393 --> 00:11:55,096
That's one of the things you don't like people to do in a meditation hall is yawn.

138
00:11:56,158 --> 00:11:58,702
Gets you going.

139
00:11:58,722 --> 00:12:08,157
Physically it's even easier because you can take the mind up and down the body and discover what parts of the body actually don't feel it.

140
00:12:09,259 --> 00:12:14,005
Like you don't feel, generally you don't feel lethargy in your toes.

141
00:12:14,025 --> 00:12:14,667
Although you can.

142
00:12:16,370 --> 00:12:18,432
If you stretch your toes you get that feeling of

143
00:12:19,460 --> 00:12:21,222
tiredness in them, or at least I do anyway.

144
00:12:23,306 --> 00:12:24,948
Maybe I've just got very sensitive toes.

145
00:12:29,076 --> 00:12:39,072
So yes, you can work with those in the same way, and you can just be aware of it, you can just feel it, you see, you can just feel it.

146
00:12:39,135 --> 00:12:53,530
You can sometimes turn your inquiry or your interest into the process or go deeper and find out what are the constituent feelings of it, the softness, hardness, softness, the gentleness.

147
00:12:53,650 --> 00:13:04,182
You can go beyond the definition of dullness and lethargy and actually find out what are the sensations that make up this concept.

148
00:13:05,663 --> 00:13:09,308
Things like that, see, awaken your interest in it.

149
00:13:10,892 --> 00:13:12,995
But sometimes it's just good enough to sit with it.

150
00:13:14,157 --> 00:13:14,817
Just walk with it.

151
00:13:14,837 --> 00:13:17,261
You know, like I say, you take the big fat dog for a walk.

152
00:13:18,264 --> 00:13:21,048
Come on, boy.

153
00:13:21,109 --> 00:13:22,169
Drag it round the paddock.

154
00:13:24,413 --> 00:13:25,596
Just keep moving the foot.

155
00:13:27,398 --> 00:13:35,025
Yeah, there was a time, there was a time those things used to, I remember distinctly, it used to last ten days with me at one point.

156
00:13:35,046 --> 00:13:52,703
I was on a long retreat and when it hit me I knew it would be around for ten days and I'd just be in this miasma for ten days and then it would slowly lift.

157
00:13:52,724 --> 00:13:55,886
So it comes and goes anyway, but over time

158
00:13:57,436 --> 00:14:08,037
if you're working with it as a constant effort in your daily life, you see, don't be brutal, you know, you're not sort of fighting it, you just know you're tired and you ask yourself, am I really tired?

159
00:14:08,057 --> 00:14:15,913
So you get up, walk around a bit, stretch, you know.

160
00:14:15,932 --> 00:14:16,033
Yeah?

161
00:14:16,052 --> 00:14:16,153
Yeah?

162
00:14:20,335 --> 00:14:23,519
So that's the question about the practice.

163
00:14:23,580 --> 00:14:27,005
We can move to one about the fetters here.

164
00:14:28,106 --> 00:14:33,515
So as I understand it, the fetters are the bindweed that generates the hindrances.

165
00:14:34,537 --> 00:14:36,841
These are always coming up in meditation and life.

166
00:14:37,522 --> 00:14:45,094
We can combat them, inverted commas, with mindfulness, but can we get all the bindweed out?

167
00:14:45,445 --> 00:14:48,328
or do we always have to be vigilant?

168
00:14:48,349 --> 00:14:52,193
I'm thinking of the delusion of a permanent self and the things that accompany this.

169
00:14:53,254 --> 00:14:57,480
As above, might cultivating positive mental states help?

170
00:14:58,400 --> 00:15:01,644
And if so, which and or and in what ways?

171
00:15:02,687 --> 00:15:04,788
Sorry it's so long.

172
00:15:05,529 --> 00:15:06,431
I like long questions.

173
00:15:08,553 --> 00:15:14,000
Well, the first thing is to be clear in our mind what these fetters are and

174
00:15:15,600 --> 00:15:17,649
what their categorization is.

175
00:15:18,091 --> 00:15:26,201
So the Buddha categorizes the human experience in various ways to give us different angles.

176
00:15:26,840 --> 00:15:44,621
Two of the ways that you can look at this psychophysical organism, the human being, is either by the khandhas, these five heaps, the body, perceptions, feelings, conditions, our habits and all that, and consciousness.

177
00:15:44,922 --> 00:15:48,186
But then he also says you can look at a human being by way of the senses.

178
00:15:48,687 --> 00:15:53,572
So there are six consciousnesses, six ways of knowing the world, the five heaps.

179
00:15:53,889 --> 00:15:56,173
physical ones and the mind itself, you see.

180
00:15:56,894 --> 00:16:05,385
So here, he first of all, I want you to point out that there's also what's known as the Anusaya.

181
00:16:06,527 --> 00:16:15,720
Now the Anusaya come very close to, I think anyway, the Western idea of something subconscious, something that we're not fully aware of.

182
00:16:17,142 --> 00:16:21,788
And it's one of these lists I haven't learned.

183
00:16:22,375 --> 00:16:29,543
They're known as, here it's translated as the proclivities, which is not a very regular word, is it?

184
00:16:29,945 --> 00:16:31,886
Inclinations or tendencies.

185
00:16:33,208 --> 00:16:34,230
Now, they won't surprise you.

186
00:16:35,030 --> 00:16:35,812
Sensuous greed.

187
00:16:37,214 --> 00:16:37,615
Grudge.

188
00:16:38,054 --> 00:16:39,157
I don't know about grudge.

189
00:16:39,697 --> 00:16:40,979
Normally hatred, yeah?

190
00:16:40,999 --> 00:16:42,701
Speculative opinion, DT.

191
00:16:42,860 --> 00:16:45,043
In other words, I'm right, everybody else is wrong.

192
00:16:46,645 --> 00:16:48,028
Skeptical doubt.

193
00:16:48,700 --> 00:17:09,257
conceit, craving for continued existence always wanting to become and ignorance which covers it all really now although this actually is enumerated I've read that the Buddha used it very generally

194
00:17:09,557 --> 00:17:37,522
the word anusaya to suggest that there were these potential conditionings within the system and that they related in some way to actual behavior to the way you think and speak and act and when they do that then you can actually see them so that's when he categorizes them in terms of our meditation practice into the five hindrances

195
00:17:37,856 --> 00:17:44,448
So now we know when something unwholesome comes up, we should be able to fit it into one of these five.

196
00:17:46,451 --> 00:17:58,633
And then when we're doing that, we're doing the fourth establishment of mindfulness, which is to see what we're experiencing by way of the Buddha's Dharma.

197
00:17:59,238 --> 00:18:01,681
dhamma-dhamma-nupāsati, right?

198
00:18:01,701 --> 00:18:07,107
To really look into the Buddha's dharma and to see what we're experiencing from his point of view.

199
00:18:07,249 --> 00:18:10,333
This is the point, you see.

200
00:18:10,813 --> 00:18:17,521
Which is difficult for us Westerners who have a different psychology and a different philosophy.

201
00:18:18,703 --> 00:18:21,988
What we tend to do is place that upon the Buddha's teaching.

202
00:18:22,711 --> 00:18:51,351
and reinterpret the Buddhist teaching by way of our understanding and I think that's some of the problems that people come across one of the early mistakes I mean it was the early Christians who came upon Buddhism and just presumed because of the descriptions of Nirvana that it was extinction

203
00:18:51,989 --> 00:19:20,493
it was often translated just annihilation even though the Buddha goes out of his way a hundred times to say he doesn't teach annihilation he only teaches the annihilation of greed, hatred and delusion so you get things like that you see so it's good sometimes to contemplate the teachings of the Buddha because it makes us see our situation in a different way and I would say that

204
00:19:22,059 --> 00:19:42,279
it's by doing that that you get the fullness of the practice I mean one example might be the quality of anicca impermanence so normally I think we would think it's the same stuff which just changes

205
00:19:43,441 --> 00:19:50,611
Like you might see a tree, the leaf of a tree, but it's always the same stuff that produces leaves.

206
00:19:50,851 --> 00:19:52,473
Do you know what I mean?

207
00:19:52,493 --> 00:19:55,778
So you get the idea that impermanence is like a cloud.

208
00:19:56,618 --> 00:19:58,101
It's the same thing, but it's changing.

209
00:19:58,642 --> 00:20:03,669
But actually, it's more like the way leaves are in a tree.

210
00:20:03,689 --> 00:20:04,851
It's a completely new leaf.

211
00:20:04,931 --> 00:20:07,795
The leaf grows, drops off, and then you get a completely new leaf.

212
00:20:08,720 --> 00:20:11,321
